AB  - In this chapter humic substances (HS) from salt marsh soils are characterized by two spectroscopic techniques single-scan fluorescence and solid-state C-13 nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy The studied soils cover a transitional gradient from predominantly marine to predominantly terrestrial environments a tidal flat vegetated by Spartina maritima (TF) a salt marsh covered by Juncus maritimus (SM) and a grassland in a active polder (GL)
   Differences in the characteristics of the HS from the three soils are detected, which may be attributed not only to the composition of the original organic material but also to environmental factors HS from TF show the lowest degree of humification and a large amount of nonpolar aliphatic components, pointing to a predominant contribution of organic materials from marine and/or microbial sources In the SM soil the suboxic conditions and the high biomass from the vegetation cover led to the accumulation of relatively fresh OM and, consequently, to a low degree of humification of the HS The HS in the GL display the highest degrees of humification and aromaticity, which may have been enhanced by the aeration and drainage of the soil by the reclamation process
   The results indicate that a wide number of factors must be considered in studying organic matter characteristics in salt marshes since they are highly variable systems at both temporal and spatial levels
