AB  - This study investigated the trophic shift of young-of-the-year (YOY) thinlip grey mullet Liza ramada and golden grey mullet Liza aurata during their recruitment in a salt marsh located on the European Atlantic Ocean coast. Stable-isotope signatures (13C and 15N) of the fishes followed a pattern, having enrichments in 13C and 15N with increasing fork length (LF): 13C in fishes<30mm ranged from 19.5 to 15.0 parts per thousand, whereas in fishes>30mm 13C ranged from 15.8 to 12.7 parts per thousand, closer to the level in salt-marsh food resources. Large differences between the 15N values of mugilids and those of food sources (6 center dot 0 parts per thousand on average) showed that YOY are secondary consumers, similar to older individuals, when feeding in the salt marsh. YOY mugilids shift from browsing on pelagic prey to grazing on benthic resources from the salt marsh before reaching 30mm LF. The results highlight the role of European salt marshes as nurseries for juvenile mugilids. (C) 2013 The Authors Journal of Fish Biology (C) 2013 The Fisheries Society of the British Isles
