AB  - Tropical marsh ecosystems play a key role in global carbon cycle. Mineralization of organic matter mediated by enzymes in such systems is of great importance in the cycle but little is known about it. This study assessed a suite of enzyme activities in two- depths of marsh soils with different water regime. Overall, enzyme activities were lower in drier soils than wet soils, suggesting water content would be a key controlling variable for decomposition in the system. Unlike northern peatland, decomposition rates may be lowered by frequent drought that is expected in the future climate.
