AB  - Atriplex portulacoides is one of the most frequent species on natural salt marshes along the French coasts and appears to be an important source of organic matter potentially available for exportation towards coastal sea waters. We followed the evolution of the biomass of this species in a macrotidal salt marsh in the ''baie du Mont-Saint-Michel'' for 3 years and at different locations in the marsh, in order to determine spatial and inter-annual variations of its productivity. Generally, Atriplex portulacoides presented a higher production in the most frequently flooded area, where environmental conditions appeared to be optimal. However, during a specific year in which a micro-lepidoptera invaded the lower part of the marsh, the primary production of Atriplex portulacoides decreased in this area. Even though this vegetation type present an apparent homogeneity, it appears important to take into account the variation of its primary production in any studies about salt-marsh functioning and exchanges with sea waters.
